John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
Scotland's independent schools have a crack performance of academic excellence, and it continued in 2018 with another set of excellent exam results, which was only strengthened by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other community businesses.
With more than 30,000 schools throughout Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their schools for further and higher education, their chosen career, and their position as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a newly created school curriculum, we see that world languages continue as a popular and desirable choice of courses.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to someone in a language he understands, it goes to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes to his heart."
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can see that languages are at the top of the league tables with the highest success rates in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a higher degree A.
The data, collected from SCIS's 74 colleges showed that 72 percent of students had received a higher grade A in Mandarins, while 72 percent of those who had studied German, 69 of those who had studied French and 63 of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young adults will no doubt need in the future.
Languages now have the same status as the STEM trades (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools' curriculums and elsewhere.
A survey by the UK Commission for Professionals and Skills found in 2014 that some of the reasons that employees provide why they are struggling to fill posts are attributed 17 percent to a lack of language skills.
Hence, language skills become more and more important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more likely jobs that languages require, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, in the future they will have a real advantage with such a lifelong skill.
To communicate directly with people from other countries, a multilingual person will automatically be placed above the competition.
According to a YouGov recording of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15 percent.
That is why investing in today’s language education is so important now.
Knowing several languages, especially those of developing economies, will equip children with a better chance to get meaningful work.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages they teach.
A number of schools will focus on the more classic modern languages, while other languages will teach what is considered essential to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarins or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare and equip children with the skills needed to succeed, regardless of what the future holds.
It cannot be denied at this stage, in a global business environment, that languages are still extremely important for the country's future, and therefore should be reflected in education.
Truly, modern languages really need to be viewed as "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity, and excellence to Scotland’s young people.
Il faut been le faire.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
