Harvard students take a course over enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year leaves all its pre-graduate students more sleep in an attempt to counter the growing macho culture of study by working coffee driven 'all-night sessions'.
A academic found that students at the world's top university are often ignorant when it concerns the basic principles of how to care for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleeping medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, designed the course, which he believed was the first of his kind in the U.S.
He was inspired to start the course after he gave a talk about the effects of sleep abduction on learning.
'At the end of it one girl approached me and said, 'Why do they tell me first, in my senior year?'
She said that no one had yet told her how important sleep was--that surprised me,' he told The Telegraph.
The course, presented for the first time this year, explains to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, as well as how it improves their general well - being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and executive director of the university’s health services, said that the university decided to enter the course after students were found to be seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The hour-long course involves some interactive tasks.
In one department there is a picture of a dormitory, where students on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books must click to be told about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is influenced by sleeplessness and the importance of a sleeptime routine.
In another department, participants are told how long-term sleep withdrawal risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer can increase.
A map of the campus, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think of their daily routine.
'We know it won't change students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know--just as you have the right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,' said Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride to 'student all night' still exists, he said, and added that modern technology and increasing pressure on students meant that sleep abduction was a growing problem.
To make sure that you get enough sleep of good quality, a student's 'secret weapon' should be to avoid stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said--even to avoid putting on weight, because sleep deprived the brain puts in a starved mode, which makes you feel hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californiar studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to design the course after he walked one of his classes last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to work for a campus course.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the institution where people compete with one another.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students consider setting an alarm for when to go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of 'blue light' emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which may disrupt your circadian rhythm and may cause you to struggle to touch the sheep.
